    <section>
      <div class="section-rule"><h2>The Allegations</h2></div>
      <p>On April 28, 2026, a civil complaint filed in New York County Supreme Court under the pseudonym "John Doe" named <strong>Lorna Hajdini</strong>, a 37-year-old executive director in JPMorgan Chase's leveraged finance division, along with the bank itself. The filing alleged a months-long campaign of sexual harassment, coercion, and racial intimidation against a junior employee.</p>
      <p>The complaint claimed Hajdini used her position of authority to coerce the employee into repeated non-consensual sexual encounters, allegedly drugging him with Rohypnol and Viagra and threatening his bonus, career progression, and livelihood if he refused to comply.</p>

      <div class="pullquote">
        <p>"If you don't comply, I'm going to ruin you… never forget, I own you."</p>
        <cite>— Alleged statement attributed to Lorna Hajdini in the original complaint</cite>
      </div>

      <p>The complaint also included allegations of racial harassment, with the plaintiff identifying as a man of Indian descent who claimed Hajdini made discriminatory remarks tied to his background. The filing went viral almost immediately, generating enormous media coverage across financial and mainstream press.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <div class="section-rule"><h2>The Bank's Response</h2></div>
      <p>JPMorgan Chase moved quickly to deny the allegations in full. A bank spokesperson stated that an internal investigation — conducted through HR and in-house legal teams — had reviewed team phone records, emails, and conducted interviews with relevant employees.</p>
      <p>"Following an investigation, we don't believe there's any merit to these claims," the spokesperson said. The bank also disclosed that the complainant had <em>refused to participate</em> in the investigation or provide facts central to his own allegations. "While numerous employees cooperated with the investigation, the complainant refused to participate and has declined to provide facts that would be central to support his allegations."</p>
      <p>Hajdini also denied all wrongdoing through her attorneys, stating she had never engaged in any inappropriate conduct with the complainant and had never visited the location where some of the alleged acts were said to have occurred.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <div class="section-rule"><h2>John Doe Unmasked</h2></div>
      <p>Within 24 hours of the filing going viral, the New York Post reported that multiple sources had identified the anonymous plaintiff as <strong>Chirayu Rana</strong>, a 35-year-old former JPMorgan staffer who at the time of reporting was working as a principal at private equity firm Bregal Sagemount.</p>
      <p>According to the Post's reporting, Rana had filed an internal complaint in May 2025 — alleging race and gender-based harassment and abuse of power — and later attempted to negotiate a severance package in the "millions." That request was rejected by the bank.</p>
      <p>Rana left JPMorgan in late 2024. He did not respond to requests for comment. Allies of Hajdini described the lawsuit as a "complete fabrication." The original court filing was subsequently withdrawn for "corrections" — a detail that drew significant scrutiny given the timing.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <div class="section-rule"><h2>Wider Scrutiny</h2></div>
      <p>The case has also drawn renewed attention to JPMorgan's broader workplace culture. Separately, <em>The Financial Times</em> reported that earlier conduct allegations involving <strong>Vis Raghavan</strong>, a former JPMorgan executive who departed for Citigroup in 2024, had previously been raised internally. Sources described Raghavan as someone who could "explode" in his office and allegedly made demeaning comments about colleagues. He denied specific allegations when questioned by HR. Raghavan secured a senior investment banking role at Citi within days of leaving JPMorgan.</p>
      <p>As of May 1, 2026, the legal situation remains fluid. The original complaint was withdrawn but could be refiled. No criminal charges have been filed. The case is expected to continue generating significant coverage as details emerge.</p>
    </section>

